{"/service/ndnp/nvln/batch_nvln_unionville_ver02/data/sn86076141/00279553767/1927031201/0060.xml":{"full_text":"LASVE6ASABE\nLas Vegas, Clark Co., Nav.\nEditor\nCHARLES P. 8QUIRE8,\nPublished every Saturday\nard entered at Las Vegas\nI postoffice as mall matter of\nthe second class.\nSubscription Terms\nOne year _..|2.00\nI Six months 1.00\nINTERNATIONAL\nSYMPATHY\nA proof that a kindly human\nfeeling exists even between na\nuona \u00abbo^\u00ab interest* are el a\ncompeting nature i\u00bb seen in the\nsympathy which goes out from\nthe people of America to. the\nJapanese stricken by the recent\nearthquake. Several thousand\npeople perished In the catas\ntrophe and many other thous\nands suffered from Injuries and\nexposure. Whole villages were\ndestroyed the inhabitants being\nlett without food or shelter from\nthe rigorous winter weather.\nUnlike the great disaster of\n1923, the present one is not so\nextensive but that the Japanese\ngovernment and people can readi\nly care for the sufferers. But, if\nit should appear that helg> U\nneeded 'the people of America\nwill again respond, not only with\nL. H. FOSTER\nU. S. MINERAL SURVEYOR\nNevada and Arizona\nADDRESS: BOX 989. KINQWAN, ARIZONA\nTYPEWRITERS\nAll Makes\nRepaired---Rebuilt\nExchanged\nWe have a good line of all makes\nrebuilt machines $30.00 to\n$60.00. Guaranteed good as new.\nWHITE CROSS DROG CO.\nCarl D. Farrar, Manager Las Vegas, Nevada\nIn MEN\u2019S SHOES We\nAlways Have Something New\nI A new leather, a distinctive new style, a dif\nferent feature of one kind or another. So, if\nyou really want to dress your feet stylishly and\ncomfortably you will head here when you want\nshoes.\nFinney Shoe Co,\n106 South Second St. Phone 277\nLOS ANGELES\nAND RETURN\nWINTER FARES\nFROM NEVADA STATIONS\nArden .$18.75\nCaliente 26.50\nJean 17.50\nLas Vegas 19.25\nMoapa 22.25\nPioche 29.25\nSloan 18.25\n$15.50\n22.25\n14.50\n16.25\n18.50\n24.25\n15.25\nTICKETS AT FARES IN FIRST COLUMN\nSOLD DAILY\u2014RETURN LIMIT 3 MONTH*.\nSECOND COLUMN, GOOD ONLY ON FRIDAYS,\nSATURDAYS AND SUNDAYS. RETURN LIMIT\n16 DAYS. OTHER FARES TO SEASHORE\nPOINTS\nUNION PACIFIC\ntheir sympathy, but with what\never financial aid is neeued. In\ntrouble we find tne world is\nrealty friendly after all.\nENCOURAGING OUTLOOK\nIt takes more than one little\nkick in the slats to make Las\nVegas downcast. The Boulder\nDam disappointment is already\nnearly forgotten and we are look\ning aheid with more hope anl\ncourage than ever before. Las\nVegas is facing a program of de\nvelopment of such importance\nthat there should be nothing but\nelation. True a few have loaded\nup rather heavily with real es\ntate expecting to reap a harvest.\nThe harvest will be slower than\nthey expected because of the de\nlay in the big project. Whether\nor not the Boulder dam is ever\nbuilt. Las Vegas real estate Is\na good investment at present\nprices.\nBut\u2014remember this. The\nBoulder Dam will be built. It is\njust as inevitable as Christmas.\nMeanwhile, Lias Vegas will make\ngood use of the intervening time\nto set her house in order for the j\nbig event, and we will be in poei-j\ntion to profit more greatly when;\nIt arrives.\nThe worst danger confronting'\nLas Vegas is the damage which I\nmay be done to our good reputa-|\ntion and future prosperity by\n\u201cwild cat\" subdivision t schemes\nand the sale of lots far and wide\nto purchasers innocent of loca\ntion or conditions. In the opinion\nof the Age, land two or three\nmiles or more from the city sub\ndivided ihto lots without im\nprovements, water sewage, lights,\nstreets or walks, is not worth one'\ndollar per jot. Its value i\u00a3r agri\nculture might have been consider\nable, but as fown 'lots this value\nIf lost.\nOur attention has been called\nto subdivisions in other places,\nnotable Victorville, Cal., and\nBaker, Cal., Which are taping of\nfered as being at the \u201cGateway\nto Boulder Dam.\" The public\nhas been duped many times and\nvery likely will be again, in spite\noi all that we can do. However,.\nit is our duty to protect the pub-j\nlie so far as we can and at the j\nsame time the good repute of I\nLas Vegas. We have plenty of j\nlegitimate propositions in which j\nthe public can safely invest. We'\nshould use every means to pro\ntect the innocent from unprin\ncipled schemers.\nOur Chamber of Commerce and\nthe Las Vegas Realty Board have\nalready given attention to this\nmatter.\nBUICK SALES SHOW\nSUBSTANTIAL CAIN\nJames Cashman, distributor of\nBuick cars, states that the new1\nmodels have met the public ap- j\nprobation in all parts of the j\ncountry as well as in the local j\n[district. There is every reason\nto bdiieve that local sales will\n[fully equal the fine record made\nby Mr. Ca&hman's organiaztion\n1 in the Las Vegas district last\nyear.\nA substantial increase in sales\nfor the first twenty days of\nFebruary over the same period\nlast year is claimed by E. T.\nStrong, president of the Buick\nMotor Company to be an indica\ntion that his company and the\nindustry in general are on the\nthreshold of one of the greatest\nselling seasons the automobile\nbusiness has ever enjoyed.\n\u201cBuick deliveries showed an\nincrease during the first twenty\ndays of February of nearly a\nMORRISON AND HIS\nMUSIC\nA Dance Band That\u2019s Here\nTo Stay\nOpen for engagement for\ndance or banquet\nSEE R. G. (Jazz) MORRISON\n\nLet vis do a neat, thor\nI ough job, giving you all\nthe comfort and con\nvenience of electricity.\nLet us install a G-E wir\ning system throughout\n\u2014with all materials\nmade by General Elec\ntric. It\u2019s the most satis\nfactory system\u2014also\nthe most economioaldor\nit lasts a lifetime.\nling System\n\u2014for lij'etim* sarvtot\nComixtently installtd by\nJ* H. Harbeson\nContracting Electrician\n19 FREMONT STREET\nthousand cars over a similar\nperiod in l\u00bb26.\" Strong said.\n\"Thi s fact coincides with the\nrecently issued statement of the\nDepartment of Commerce which\nsaid that business for the third\nweak \u201ein February exceeded any\npreceding week this year, and\nthat the sharp increase in bank\n'clearances indicated a favorable\nbusiness outlook. We have found\nthat automobile sales a tv an ac\ncurate index of general business\nconditions. The steady increase\nin Buick business during the vast\nfew weeks is a favorable sign.\n\u2019\u2019\u2019phe value in using these sales\nfigures as an index lies in the\nfact that there has been nothing\ndone to stimulate sales or create\na demand Which might be con\ntrary to general conditions. The\nmodels now on the market are\nthe ones introduced last August\nwith the exception of two addi\ntional body styles which were\nadded to the Hne later. Thus\nthe upward trend in sales can be\nattributed to more favorable\nbusiness conditions.\u2019\nASSOCIATED PRESS MAN\nENJOYS FLYING TOUR\nR. G. Smith, manager of the\nAssociated Press at Salt I^ake\nCity, was a passenger through\nLas Vegas on a plane of the\nWestern Air Express from Los\nAngeles to Salt Lake Wednesday\nmorning.\nMr. Smith is making the round\ntrip, Salt Lake-San Francisco,Los\nAngeles by air. He has made\nother tripw by air but this is the\nlongest. He states that he en\njoys that mode of travel and is\ncomplimentary of the service\nfurnished by the Western Air\nExpress.\nMr. Smith plans to put out\nsome art idles on the places of\nhistoric and scenic interest about\nLas Vegas, such as the Buried\nCity, For.t Callville, etc.\nWEATHER REPORT.\nMONTH OF FEBRUARY\nThe maximum and minimum\ntemperatures for the month of\nFebruary as shown by the rec\nords of the U. S. Cooperative\nweather observer at Las Vegas,\nare as follows:\nMax. Min. 6 p.m.\nFebruary 1 67 28\nFebruary 2 68 30\nFebruary 3 68 33\nFelbruary 4 60 33\nFebruary 5 79 30\nFebruary 6 74 32\nFebruary 7 70 33\nFebruary 8 71 32\nFebruary 9 65 30\nFebruary 10 71 30\nFebruary 11 68 31\nFebruary 12 63 28\nFebruary 13 52 28\nFebruary 14 56 40 51\nFebruary 15 61 43 45\nFebruary 16 65 46 57\nFebruary 17 62 42 5.8\nFebruary 18 79 40\nFebruary 19 79 50 61\nFebruary 20 70 39 60\nFebruary 21 72 40 60\nFebruary 22 72 41 60\nFebruary 23 70 42 62\nFelbruary 24 72 46 59\nFebruary 25 79 45 68\nFebruary 26 79 45 69\nFebruary 27 80 43 71\nFebruary 28 68 43 60\nA measurable amount of rain\nfell on February 14, 15 and 16,\nthe total for the month being\n.90 inches. Traces fell on sev\neral other days. The rainfall\nwhile small in quantity came\nslowly, there being very little\nrunoff. Pasturage is much bene\nfitted and the water resources\nwill be replenished by the heavy\nsnows which fell in the higher\nalititudes. The mountains about\nLas Vegas are more heavily\nblanketed with snow than for\nseveral years past.\nLESS CATTLE MORE\nSHEEP IN NEVADA\nThe number of cattle in Ne\nvada decreased from 419,000 on\nJanuary 1, 1925, to 366,000 on\nthe first of this year, but the\nnumber of sheep and lambs in\ncreased, according to a report\njust made public by George S.\nScott, regional statistician for the\nUnited States department of\nagriculture. The report on cattle\nadds, however, that Nevada dairy\nstock shows a gain during the\nperiod increasing from 19,000 two\nyears ago, to 20,000 on the first\nof this year.\nThe report credits Nevada with\n1,260,000 sheep and lambs on the\nfirst of this year as compared\nwith 1,100,000 two years ago.\nSwine increased during the period\nfrom 26,000 'to 26,000. Horses\nand colts decreased in -number\nfrom fifty thousand to 44,000.\nThe state is credited with four\nthousand mules, the same that\nit had two years ago.\u2014Gazette.\n18 MILES AN HOUR\nRECORD 17 YEARS AGO\nSeventeen years ago a Texas\neditor fqund news in the fact\nthat a Buick Model 10 traveled\na distance of ninety miles at an\naverage speed of eighteen miles\nan hour. The item read:\n\"Last Saturday Mr. and Mrs.\nJ. W. Moore started out towards\nPort Stockton with their twenty\nhorsepower Buick Model 10, go\ning forty-ftvt miles 6ut and re\nturn and making the distance in\nfive hours.\u201d Then was added\nthis editorial opinion: \u201cThat cer\nj tainly is making splendid time\nover country roads.\u201d\nThis model was the first hori\nzontal four cylinder valve-in-head\nBuick ever built, and was quite\na sensation in its day. It was\nin this car that Louis .Chevrolet,\nBoh Burman and others gained\nfame as automobile racing driv\nersL Many of the stock car rec\nords they set seventeen years\nago still stand on the record\nbooks. In one year the Model\n10 was started in several hund\nred races, finishing first In the\ngreat majority of them. Among\nthe racing records set by a Buick\ncar was the 250 mile Indianapolis\nrecord, stood for many\nyears\nI. S. THOMPSON GOES\nTO VEGAS. MAKE HOME\n(Tonopah Bonanza)\nI. S. Thompson, one of the\npioneer attorneys of southern\nNevada, expects to leave Tono\npah next Thursday morning to\nopen an office In Las Vegas. His\nlaw library will be moved to the\nsouthern town tomorrow <by\ntruck. Judge Thompeon, follow\ning his graduation, from the Uni\nversity of Michigin, and after\npracticing in San Jose, went to\nGoldfield in 1904. He went there\ndirectly from Alaska, where he\nhad bean doing special work for\nthe government in criminal cases.\nIn Goldfield he took his\nbrother, the late J. G. Thompson,\ninto partnership, and later the\nfirm became Thompson, More\nhouse and Thompson, which was\nengaged in some of the most\nnoted civil and criminal cases in\nthe busy days of the gold town.\nAmong these suits was the fam\nous mining case of the Mohawk\nagainst the Frances Mohawk.\nThe firm represented the D. Mc\nKenzie Interests in the case.\nJudge Thompson moved to Tono\npah at the time of the Divide\nboom, remained two years, and\nthen returned to Goldfield to get\nin on another boom there. At\nthe colapse of the last excite\nment in Goldfield, he return'd\nto Tonopah .three years ago. He\nis going to Las Vegas, he said,\nto be established when Boulder\nCanyon dam is begun, as he pre\ndicts that the dam wM make a\nbig city fo' Las Vegas. He has\na great many friends tn Tonopah\nwho will regret his decision to\nmove.\nisHOULin\nBE MORE!\n|carefulj\nCOMMON SENSE\nis the cop that\nwarms you to be\ncarefull. See that\nyour brakes and\n\u25a0steering fleaT are\nworking right be\nfore you start out.\nMake sure that\nyour engine isn\u2019t\ngoing dead while\nyou're on your trip.\nSee to it that your car is proper\nly lunbricated. All of these are\nour duties.\nThe Shop That Gives Your\nDollar a Long Ride\nLas Vegas Garage\n216 Fremont St. Phone 73\nJ. F. HENRY\nSERVICE STATION\nTHIRD AND FREMONT\nSTEAM VULCANIZIN6\nWE GUARANTEE ALL\nBOTH BALLOON AND\nHIGH PRESSURE TIRES\nSome of our statesmen and col\nlege professors seem to be In\nfavor of the nationalist move\nment in Mexico and China but\nagainst any nationalism in the\nUnited State*.\nCATHOLIC CHURCH\nCbaa. A. Edward*, pastor.\nMasses\nSundays\u20148:00 and 10:00 a. in.\nWeek days\u20148:00 a. m.\nMatch Winds\nBring much sickness, which usually requires a\ndoctor\u2019s advice, a prescription is necessary, and\nmust be filled by experts using fresh drugs.\nWe are experts.\ni\nHudson-Graglia Drug Co.\nR. HUDSON J. GRAGLIA\nKEEPING YOUR TEETH\nHEALTHY IS YOUR DUTY\nIn a greater measure than most peo\nple realize, their health and enjoyment\nof life depends upon the condition of\ntheir teeth. This being true, you cer\ntainly owe it to yourself to use every\nprecaution to keep them healthy. Use\nKlenzo Tooth Paste.\nLAS YECAS PHARMACY\nW. E. FERRON THE REXALL STORE\nEd. W. Clark\nForwarding Co.\nWHOLESALE and RETAIL\nWo Buy Our Hay, Grain, Flour, Canned Goods,\nCoal, Ete., in Carload Lots\nLARGEST WHOLESALERS OF FOODSTUFFS AND\nFARM PRODUCTS IN SOUTHERN NEVADA\nWE CARRY A FULL LINE OF FANCY QROCERIES.\nHARDWARE AND GENTS' FURNISHINGS\nLUMBER\nYou Can Depend\nUpon\nTHERE is Lumber and Lumber. One kind, the sort we sell,\nis Lumber that you can use as needed, with the assurance\nthat it will serve the purpose 